<DOC><DOCNO> AP881028-0306 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-28-88 1337EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-ShortStint     10-28 0239</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Short Stint,0250</SECOND><HEAD>Ralph Martino Will Have a Very Peculiar Resume</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Ralph Martino had a short career at ATandamp;T. Soshort, in fact, that the company was still announcing his arrivalthe day after he quit.   Setting a new standard for revolving-door employment, Martinospent two days this week as the executive in charge of ATandamp;T's1,000-member computer sales force before returning to his oldemployer, IBM.   ``He started working Monday morning and he left Tuesdayafternoon,'' Dick Muldoon, a spokesman for American Telephone andamp;Telegraph Co., said Friday.   ``We are absolutely assured that his decision was personal and itwas not because he was dissatisfied with business plans ordirections,'' Muldoon added.   Martino, 38, served his brief stint as national sales vicepresident at ATandamp;T's Data Systems Group in Morristown, N.J.   ATandamp;T executives were still telling securities analysts about thehigh-level appointment as late as Wednesday, not realizing their manwas gone, the Wall Street Journal reported Friday.   International Business Machines Corp. said Martino is on specialassignment to David M. Thomas, president of the NationalDistribution Division in Montvale, N.J. He worked previously inIBM's Applications Systems Division in Valhalla, N.Y., overseeingsoftware development.   ``All I know is he left and after one day he decided to return.He does not want to be interviewed,'' IBM spokesman Douglas DeLaysaid.   ATandamp;T's Muldoon added: ``He was very well respected _ at bothcompanies.''</TEXT></DOC>